about.summary: Fit linear and generalized linear mixed models with various extensions, including zero-inflation. The models are fitted using maximum likelihood estimation via 'TMB' (Template Model Builder). Random effects are assumed to be Gaussian on the scale of the linear predictor and are integrated out using the Laplace approximation. Gradients are calculated using automatic differentiation.

name: r-glmmtmb
raw_meta_yaml:
{% set version = "0.2.3" %}
{% set posix = 'm2-' if win else '' %}
{% set native = 'm2w64-' if win else '' %}

package:
  name: r-glmmtmb
  version: {{ version|replace("-", "_") }}

source:
  fn: glmmTMB_{{ version }}.tar.gz
  url:
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/glmmTMB_{{ version }}.tar.gz
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/Archive/glmmTMB/glmmTMB_{{ version }}.tar.gz
  sha256: 6b6f62addaa54b32b975bc984110e245330749ebf69bed4a297f9da1b89fb00c

build:
  merge_build_host: True  # [win]
  number: 1
  skip: true  # [win32]
  rpaths:
    - lib/R/lib/
    - lib/

requirements:
  build:
    - {{ compiler('c') }}        # [not win]
    - {{ compiler('cxx') }}      # [not win]
    - {{ compiler('m2w64_c') }}        # [win]
    - {{ compiler('m2w64_cxx') }}        # [win]
    - {{posix}}filesystem        # [win]
    - {{posix}}make
    - {{posix}}sed               # [win]
    - {{posix}}coreutils         # [win]
    - {{posix}}zip               # [win]
  host:
    - r-base
    - r-matrix
    - r-rcppeigen
    - r-tmb >=1.7.13
    - r-lme4 >=1.1_10
    - r-nlme
  run:
    - r-base
    - {{native}}gcc-libs         # [win]
    - r-matrix
    - r-rcppeigen
    - r-tmb >=1.7.13
    - r-lme4 >=1.1_10
    - r-nlme

test:
  commands:
    - $R -e "library('glmmTMB')"           # [not win]
    - "\"%R%\" -e \"library('glmmTMB')\""  # [win]

about:
  home: https://github.com/glmmTMB
  license: AGPL-3
  summary: Fit linear and generalized linear mixed models with various extensions, including
    zero-inflation. The models are fitted using maximum likelihood estimation via 'TMB'
    (Template Model Builder). Random effects are assumed to be Gaussian on the scale
    of the linear predictor and are integrated out using the Laplace approximation.
    Gradients are calculated using automatic differentiation.
  license_family: AGPL

extra:
  recipe-maintainers:
    - conda-forge/r
    - johanneskoester
    - bgruening
    - daler
    - jdblischak
    - cbrueffer
    - dbast
    - ccwang002
